<body>

<h1>@HI{{shika}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> ... V(negative)
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> ... V(negative)
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> follows nouns and quantifiers and is always used with a negative
predicate. Its function is to highlight the word and express the idea that everything except the
marked word is negated. It carries a negative nuance.
</p>

<p>
After a noun, <strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> indicates that there is nothing more than the quantity specified with the
suggestion that the quantity is small.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KT{{ro-maji}}@KJ{{character}}<strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong>@KJ{{write}}@HI{{masenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I cannot write anything except Roman letters.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{store}}niha,kono@KJ{{miscellaneous^document}}<strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong>arimasendeshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This was the only magazine at that store.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
After a verb, <strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong>  indicates a limit to the action specified by the verb.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{iyadakeredo,@KJ{{exit^lengthen}}dakara@KJ{{going}}u<strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong>nai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't want to, but since it's a business trip I can't help but go.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When <strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> follows a noun + @HI{{ga}} or noun + @HI{{wo}},
<strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> replaces those particles.
For all other particles, <strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> follows them rather than replacing them.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{shika}}</strong> may follow <a href="grammar-particle-dake.html">@HI{{dake}}</a>,
@HI{{nomi}} and @HI{{kiri}} for additional emphasis.
</p>

